{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7cd09b3b-9c47-4f19-82a0-f4e1428912de","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions during evaluation is **synchronous and blocking**. This runs on every evaluation (IDE hover, restore, build) and bypasses caching. Move file reading to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` instead.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree** on every evaluation. If this project grows or sits alongside large folders (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`), evaluation time will spike. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low Impact — but compounds)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels is manageable, but each import adds file-existence checks and XML parsing. In larger repos this pattern can balloon. Keep import depth shallow.\n\n---\n\n**Recommended fixes:**\n1. Replace `File::ReadAllText` with a target that reads at build time.\n2. Narrow the glob: e.g., `**\\*.txt` or add exclusions for known large dirs.\n3. Flatten the import chain if the intermediate files carry little logic.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"714c391c-db0d-45d4-b425-88d97d0906e6","outputTokens":386,"requestId":"F021:5F08B:1313FE7:1594201:69F9452F"},"id":"93cacf24-409a-4cf1-924f-52d8b80b3317","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:17:45.397Z","parentId":"60d881f0-3178-4f10-bc1d-5c9b5873d318"}
